to hagion&quot;; &quot;the spirit the holy (spirit)&quot;.  Normally, when the word
&quot;hagion&quot; (holy) follows &quot;pneuma&quot; (spirit) it is used as an adjective.
In Greek the adjective comes after the noun it modifies but in English
before the noun it modifies.  So, normally, &quot;to pneuma hagion&quot; would
be rendered &quot;the holy spirit&quot; beause the adjective is moved to the
front of &quot;pneuma&quot; so the ENglish would read &quot;the holy spirit.&quot;

