&quot;to pneuma to hagion&quot; occurs.  The second definite article &quot;to&quot; before
&quot;hagion&quot; causes &quot;hagion&quot; to be come a noun.  Greek adjectives become
nouns when they are preceded by the definite aticle.  Therefore, since
&quot;hagion&quot; is a noun the editors had no authority to drop the second
definite article, change the noun back to an adjective, or convert the
common noun (pneuma) and the common known (hagion) to a proper
